      <div class="tabpage" id="tabpage_2">
          <h2>Causes & Risk Factors</h2>
          <p align="justify">
          Warts are caused by viruses belonging to the human papilloma family. There are over 100 types of HPV viruses. While some people do not seem to get warts easily and are naturally resistant to the HPV virus, the others don’t. Warts can grow anywhere on your body including the skin, genitals, rectal area or insides of the mouth. The more common HPV viruses cause warts on the skin while other types cause warts on the rectal or genital areas.
          </p>
      </div>
      <div class="tabpage" id="tabpage_3">
          <h2>Symptoms & Signs</h2>
          <p align="justify">
              Symptoms:<br><br>
-  Raised or flat, small, round lesions or lumps anywhere on the skin<br>
•    Rough growths under and around toenails or fingernails<br>
•    Abnormally light or dark skin surrounding a lesion<br>
•    Several smooth, small (pinhead sized), flat lesions on cheeks, forehead, arms or legs<br>
•    Oval or round, rough, flat or raised lesions on the soles of the feet that might hurt under pressure.
          </p></div>
	  <div class="tabpage" id="tabpage_4">
              <h2>Treatment</h2>
              <p align="justify">
                  a.  Medical<br>
                  A number of medications available over the counter are effective in the treatment of warts. These medications, when applied to the warts on a daily basis, regularly for several weeks, have a tendency to file the warts down. The medication is applied when a wart is damp, typically after a shower. However, warts that appear on the face or genitals should only be treated with medication that your doctor prescribes. <br>
You doctor may recommend stronger medication like salicylic acid or podophyllin to remove persistent warts. Gardasil, a vaccine that prevents infection caused by certain strains of HPV viruses may also be used for treatment or to prevent reoccurrence of warts.<br>
Immunotherapy, a procedure in which a substance is injected into your body, or a topical medication (imiquimod) may be considered by your doctor. <br><br>
b. Surgical<br>
Surgical techniques such as cryotherapy (freezing), electrocautery (burning) or laser treatment may be required to remove warts.  
              </p>    
